A Czech arbitrates the fight for the seabed
It approaches a wall-mounted electronic map, on which Australia and adjacent marine areas are depicted.
Now, he is not interested in the continent, but in a small point lost in the blue of the ocean.
"The island belongs to Australia, as does the adjacent seabed.
Yet this area is as large as the continent itself,” says Italian jurist Luigi Santosuosso, who is part of the 30-member team of the UN Division for Oceans and Law of the Sea.
Its head, the director of the division, the Czech jurist Václav Mikulka, follows the presentation and completes it from time to time.
The ardour at work and enthusiasm characterize the reigning atmosphere.
The seabed hides a little-known world so far, rich in natural resources.
Oil, minerals and other mineral resources can be found here, as well as currently unknown living organisms, which may hold the key to the development of a cancer drug.
A background larger than the mainland
The coastal states have now begun to aspire vehemently to the new submarine territories.
According to a UN convention, they are in fact using their rights, on which they agreed in 1982 in Montego Bay, Jamaica.
This is mainly the area of what is called the continental shelf, which often extends several hundred kilometers from the coast of the given country.
The latter may, according to the Convention, claim exclusively to all the resources of the continental shelf.
"To simplify, the part of the seabed and its subsoil, which is a natural extension of the continent under the sea, is considered a continental shelf.
It extends beyond the limits of the coastal sea, often also beyond the two hundred nautical miles that represent the so-called exclusive economic yona," Mikulka explains.
The request that the country in question submits to the Commission for the establishment of the external borders of the continental shelf, must be supported by extensive scientific and technical documentation, based on many costly explorations and metrics.
It is the result of several years of preparatory work.
"One of our roles is to provide the commission with legal and scientific-technical assistance.
So far, the committee has dealt with five requests, those from Russia, Brazil, Australia, Ireland and New Zealand.
So far, only the last three countries mentioned have been successful," adds Mikulka.
The success of Australia, which is the first to have significantly expanded its submarine holdings, has recently experienced global resounding.
New Zealand, too, has gained territory - the extent of the seabed, which the commission assigned to it last week, corresponds to 1.6 million square kilometers, which represents the size of the country multiplied by six.
Both countries have invested millions of dollars in prospecting.
The future benefits they will derive from the exploitation of the seabed will be, as they plan, invaluable.
Gradually, other countries will, in turn, submit their requests.
They can do so within ten years of ratifying the "Montego Bay Convention".
There, where the continental shelf ends, begins the zone of the ocean floor, proclaimed by convention "common heritage of humanity".
There, no longer any state enjoys an exclusive position.
The right of extraction in this zone is granted by an international institution established by convention.
"Nevertheless, do not be mistaken, the seabed is not a Klondike," says exaggerating Director Mikulka, noting that "its zones are precisely clearly defined and their regime anchored in a contract."
Czechs in the Pacific
Part of the seabed now also belongs to the Czech Republic.
It shares it with other states of the former bloc of the Eastern countries within the framework of the joint organization "Interoceanmetal".
In 1991, the Commission, together with investors from a few other States, was granted the status of a so-called "pioneer investor" under the Convention.
It has the right of extraction in the ClarionClipperton area in the Pacific Ocean, located between Mexico, the Hawaiian Islands and Kiribati.
The area prospected by the investor slightly exceeds the area of the former Czechoslovakia.
The bottom is turbulent, it is a kind of underwater replica of the Tatra.
"It is possible to extract on an area with a total area of 75,000 square kilometers.
The area represents a deposit rich in polymetallic concretions containing nickel, copper, cobalt and manganese," says Ind Pakshi Rajan, another lawyer.
Rober Sandev, a Macedonian employee of the division, gives an example of such a concreteness.
It is reminiscent of a small potato, or, with a little imagination, the mythical shoem, which, according to legend, animated the Golem.
