Organizers report an increasing number of bookings
This should be a good winter for German travel agencies:
In terms of bookings for the coming months, according to a study, the turnover has increased significantly compared to the previous year - for the winter season, even by more than 30 percent.
Despite weak economic prospects, the Germans’ thirst for travel remains insatiable, according to this study.
As for bookings for the winter season, travel agencies recorded a turnover of more than 31 percent compared to the same period the previous year, as confided Monday in Berlin the German Federation of Travel Agencies (DRV).
According to the survey by the GfK Market Research Institute, growing numbers of bookings already dominate the fall months.
Thus the sales figure would have risen to about 11 percent more compared to 2007, according to DRV.
The sources of these results are the figures from GfK, which analyzes monthly booking data from 1,200 travel agencies and makes estimates for the global market.
Travel bookings made since the end of August 2008 would be recorded there.
Due to the low price of the dollar, travel to the U.S. would be particularly in demand, the DRV said.
There, the increase in bookings would amount to about a third.
Besides this, Spain, Turkey and Greece as well as our country would be particularly sought after destinations by the Germans.
Specially organized trips are in high demand, explained DRV President Klaus Laepple.
In view of the rising prices of energy and food products, the costs would be here "easier to calculate for the customer than for an individually organized trip".
Consumers can save money, among other things, with early booking discounts or All Inclusive offers, Laepple explained.
The summer months were also very tight so that an increase in sales figures will again be recorded compared to last year - although according to another study, the number of Germans who undertook a trip has decreased compared to the previous year.
