In November, Honda will begin the commercialization of the second generation of the Jazz model.
If its predecessor already had a good habitability, this new minivan has an even larger interior space.
Added to this are some refined mechanics, which increase driving comfort and save more gasoline.
An evolution in the face of a revolution.
This is the second generation of the Honda Jazz.
Although aesthetically the new Honda Jazz presents a line very similar to the previous model, the changes introduced in this minivan are numerous.
Among them, there is an innovative design, a new platform, larger dimensions and new engines.
However, before examining the new model, it should be noted that this new Honda Jazz arrives six years after the market launch of the first generation.
First of all, we note that Honda renewed this model in a shorter time than other manufacturers.
Although in Europe, the Honda Jazz is less known, this model is a phenomenon of sales in other markets.
This is the case of Japan, where the Honda Jazz was the most commercialized car in 2002 and also in 2008.
Precisely in Japan, almost one million Honda Jazz have been sold since its launch.
The Old Continent, with more or less one million cars sold in six years, stands in second place.
However, Honda claims that this new Jazz will allow it to increase its sales in Europe.
Thus, while in 2007 the Japanese brand marketed 83,000 Honda Jazz, in 2009 it expects to sell 100,000, which would represent a sales growth of 17% in the European market.
In the Spanish market, Honda has sold 8,000 Jazz since 2002, which represents 6.7% of Honda sales in Spain.
