A week after unveiling an interim deal, the two banks explained that MUFG would buy 9.9% of Morgan Stanley common shares at a unit price of $25.25, or a total amount of $3 billion.
The retained price is 19% lower than the book value of the securities as at 31 August.
MUFG will invest an additional $6 billion in the acquisition of convertible securities with a 10% return and a conversion price of $31.25.
Morgan Stanley said the overall transaction would be based on an average unit price of $29, or 28 percent above its current price.
Morgan Stanley, however, lost 6.79% at $23.07 at 17:00 GMT.
“This strategic alliance is an important opportunity to accelerate Morgan Stanley’s transition to banking holding status,” said John Mack, CEO of Morgan Stanley.
Morgan Stanley adopted this new statute last week, which should allow it to diversify its activities but passes it under the authority of the Federal Reserve.
Its alliance with MUFG also confirms that the current financial crisis is forcing the biggest names on Wall Street to adopt a much more cautious attitude than before.
The terms presented Monday further show that the deal has been modified over the past few days: last Monday, Morgan had simply announced that it would sell up to 20% of its shares to the Japanese for about $8.5 billion.
“A week ago,” Toshihide Mizuno, executive director of MUFG, told Tokyo, “we thought that the stake would be composed entirely of common shares.
But given the current economic and market situation, we wanted to minimize the risks and cover ourselves.”
On the basis of the weighted average price, MUFG will pay its Morgan Stanley securities 7% below their book value.
And the transaction will result in a dilution of about 20% of earnings per share.
The agreement stipulates that MUFG will be able to convert half of its preferred shares into common shares within one year if the shares are traded more than 50% above the conversion price, or at approximately $47, during a given period.
Morgan Stanley ensures that the capital provided by MUFG will enable it to seize investment opportunities, strengthen its balance sheet and increase its liquidity.
However, a spokeswoman for the group declined to elaborate on the strategic plans of the two new allies.
Following MUFG’s investment, Morgan Stanley is expected to have a Tier One solvency ratio of about 15%, one of the best in the industry.
Morgan said it had "clearly" eased its balance since the end of August.
The last few weeks have been challenging for the group, which has seen its stock price fall by half as the cost of default risk insurance on its debt soars.
This cost fell on Monday but remained at a high level, around 12%.
Last week, Goldman Sachs, the only other “survivor” of the big Wall Street investment banks after the bankruptcies of Bear Stearns and Lehman Brothers and the takeover of Merrill Lynch, announced it had raised $15 billion, in part from Berkshire Hathaway, the group of Warren Buffett.
Rafael Correa in Quito, this Monday.
To refound the republic around the socialism of the 21st century.
This is the joint project of Venezuelan Hugo Chávez, Bolivian Evo Morales and Ecuadorian Rafael Correa.
This Sunday, like his counterparts and friends, it is the third that put to the vote a draft new Constitution.
Mission accomplished since 64% of voters voted "yes" in the referendum, according to official results covering 80% of the votes.
According to these results, the "no" got 28%, 7% of the votes were null and 0.7% were white votes.
For the draft constitution to be adopted, he had to win half of the votes plus one.
On Sunday, two polls carried out at the exit of the polling stations and a counting of a non-governmental organization announced a large victory of the "yes", placing it between 63% and 70%.
Rafael Correa claimed the victory of his draft constitution on Sunday night.
The “Constitution triumphed overwhelmingly,” he said, congratulating Ecuadorians at the Guayaquil governorate headquarters, 280 kilometers southwest of Quito.
Of course, Rafael Correa was congratulated by Chávez and Morales but also his Chilean counterpart Michelle Bachelet.
The vote, which took place calmly according to the observation mission of the Organization of American States (OAS), focused on a text in 444 points consolidating the "new socialism" defended by the president.
The draft Constitution enshrines the state's power over the economy, reserving it for the "development planning" of a country living essentially from the extraction of oil by foreign companies and the currencies sent by its emigrants.
Led by Correa, elected in 2006, the bill also grants the head of state strengthened powers, which can carry out up to two consecutive four-year terms and will have the opportunity to dissolve the Assembly.
Correa has already announced that he will use this power and run for a new term in February 2009.
The Constitution also consolidates the principle of free health and education services that the President has begun to establish in this country of 13.9 million inhabitants, where 50 per cent of the population lives below the poverty line.
Finally, it provides for a ban on the presence of foreign troops, which will end the agreement between Quito and Washington for the use of an Ecuadorian base as a starting point for U.S. anti-drug operations.
The 19 hostages have been released in Chad
An Egyptian commando has launched the assault against the kidnappers of the eleven tourists and their eight companions captured ten days ago.
They are in Cairo.
The eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian escorts held captive for ten days in the desert were brought safely back to the Egyptian capital on Monday afternoon.
In the morning, they had been released by an Egyptian commando in Chad.
Apparently in good shape, the hostages arrived at around 3:30 p.m. aboard a special aircraft at the al-Maza military base, which is adjacent to Cairo International Airport.
They were immediately transferred, without being able to speak to the press, aboard helicopters to the hospital in Maadi, a residential suburb of Cairo, for examination.
They are in "good health" and "no ransom has been paid" to the kidnappers, Egyptian Tourism Minister Zoheir Garanna said on the tarmac.
Captured on September 19 during a 4x4 safari at the foot of Mount Ouanat, on the borders of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, this group of hostages had been tossed from one cache to another by 35 unknown kidnappers.
It includes 11 tourists - five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian - as well as eight Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, a border guard and the director of the agency Aegyptous, organizer of the safari.
An Egyptian security official said 30 members of the special forces, brought aboard two helicopters, launched the assault in the night just before dawn.
"An exchange of gunfire occurred, and half of the kidnappers were killed, the others fleeing," said the official, who requested anonymity.
He said that 150 members of the Egyptian special forces of the "lightning" unit had been sent in total to Sudan, where they received support from German and Italian commandos.
Italian Foreign Minister Franco Frattini mentioned from Belgrade, where he is, the role played by secret agents and elements of Italian special forces.
"We must recognize that we have achieved this result thanks to the professionalism and efficiency of our Secret Service and Special Forces personnel," he said.
He also denied paying a ransom.
The day before, the Sudanese army claimed to have intercepted during a patrol a 4x4 vehicle in which the kidnappers were, killing six, including the Chadian leader, and arresting two.
The army said they were linked to a rebel group in Darfur, the Sudanese Unity Liberation Movement (SLA-U), which the movement immediately denied.
Letters - The Silent Majority of Culture
A debate about the financing of culture is making headlines and occupying this election campaign.
I'm glad you did.
But an area of our cultural life is still forgotten.
Who will stand up to denounce the sums of misery granted to small museums, archives, archaeological excavations or national historic sites that are starving?
What politician would dare remind the federal government that it neglects its monuments and heritage buildings?
That in Quebec, as in Canada, we do not have real laws that effectively preserve our heritage?
Did you know that the French government is spending three and a half million euros on the restoration of the only castle in Chinon in the Loire Valley?
In our American neighbors, it is written in the Constitution of their country that the protection of heritage is part of the culture of Americans and that this heritage must be protected by all citizens, all elected officials and all government departments, and this, in concert.
In Quebec, at the Fédération des sociétés d'histoire du Québec, at least 40,000 volunteers grouped in 211 societies of history, heritage, archives and genealogy are concerned with digging through history, preserving with three under piles of private archives and preserving archaeological remains.
It is they, often, who are the watchdogs of our heritage, who protest with the energy of despair when promoters and decision makers throw their bulldozers against our old stones and forgotten cemeteries.
When, a forum for history and heritage?
Benelux governments nationalize part of Fortis bank
The Benelux states help the Belgian-Dutch bank, as the first European banking institution in distress following the snowball effect of the credit market crisis in the United States, by partially nationalizing it. The three countries support, with a sum of 11.2 billion euros, this financial and insurance institution also having interests in Hungary.
This weekend, the Belgian, Luxembourg and Dutch governments agreed, at the highest level, on this case, also calling on the European Central Bank and the European Commission’s Competition Officer.
In the euro area, the first major crisis in the context of the growing international financial crisis in more than a year is for Fortis Bank. In some respects, the decisions that will be taken in the case of this bank will serve as a precedent.
In accordance with the decision taken on Sunday night, the three states will repurchase almost half (to the extent of 49%) of the capital of the bank located in each of the countries.
The bank will undoubtedly sell a part of its stakes, among which, in the first place, the activities, mainly insurance, which it acquired last year from the Dutch body ABN Amro.
Last week, Fortis stocks began a dizzying fall. In the second half of the week, serious signs of crisis have already been revealed at the bank.
Analysts agree that with its 85,000 employees, the bank is far too big to let go of bankruptcy.
On Friday alone, the company’s shares fell 12 percent to their lowest level of 14 years ago.
Since January, stocks have fallen by more than two-thirds of their value.
Taking into account the present value of the shares, the total value of the group’s capital is around 14 billion euros, which, according to the company’s managers, is not realistic.
The company's management accuses the uncertainty in the U.S., in connection with the adoption of the $700 billion U.S. bailout, of being behind the crash of Fortis shares.
On Monday, the papers have already benefited from a slight increase.
On Friday, Filip Dierckx was appointed to head the bank, as the new CEO.
The financial institution was also looking for private buyers, but has not yet received a proposal on the merits.
Previously, the Belgian government announced that investors should not worry, they are not going to lose their money.
No panic was felt in the bank’s customer circle and no branch was stormed.
In Hungary, Fortis has independent agencies and has also acquired leasing companies.
A fox in the chicken coop
In America, life and health insurance companies frequently refuse to sign an insurance contract with a candidate based on information about their drug purchases.
Information protection experts fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
"There are data protection programs that link the use of information regarding the prescription of medicines, in all cases, with the consent of the data subject.
This kind of program has to be in independent hands, otherwise it’s like entrusting your chicken coop to a fox,” Richard Dicket, the creator of the program used to manage prescription drugs, told The Washington Post.
Insurance companies make the insurance premium and the insured capital in the event of damage depend on the state of health of the client that arises, and if they feel that the risk is too great, they do not even insure it.
In the past, they sent candidates for a medical examination, and they only signed an insurance contract with them after learning about the results.
For the past ten years, Dick has found a much cheaper procedure: from an identification number, he easily provides from pharmacies, data on the purchases of medicines of the person in the past eighteen months. From this, the program determines itself, which disease the person suffers and what his state of health is.
For example, if that person regularly buys high doses of cholesterol lowering, this refers to an extremely high level of fat in the blood, which immediately puts him or her in a higher risk category.
Several versions of this program are in circulation. Some at the same time determine a risk coefficient, so there is not much more to do for the insurer besides paperwork. However, tiny problems may still appear.
Among the disadvantages of this program is the fact that a drug can be used for different purposes. For example, some mixtures can be used against migraine or hot flashes, but can also be effective against depression.
The latter is considered by insurers as an aggravating risk factor, while the others are not.
Companies have developed in the research and analysis of data. They must ask the patient for permission before collecting the necessary information from the pharmacy.
Henceforth, they are forced to do so by the authorities, even if they have not been sanctioned for their failures in the past.
Recently, some companies have also processed the results of laboratory tests and linked them to data on drug use, thus providing an even more accurate picture of the health status of patients.
More and more companies have access to data, and at the same time controlling usage is becoming increasingly difficult.
There is a separate law on the protection of medical data, but its scope extends only to practitioners and insurers.
A proposal for a law on the extension of the control circle of authorities concerning companies specializing in the provision of data is currently before Congress.
Dick Richard acknowledges that this is not enough and that is why he has further developed his program, which would condition the transmission of data to the exclusive agreement of the data subject.
It is another question of whether the person concerned is really free to give his consent or not, since if he refuses, the insurances do not sign an insurance contract with him.
Thus and ultimately, the hens depend on the fox’s benevolence.
The global menu of Marseille
The European Union and India are doubling their trade.
Since the European Union and India are very important trading partners for each other, this issue also dominated the agenda of this ninth summit alongside the other, largely global, issues.
Today, there will also be a France-India summit, which will focus on cooperation in the field of atomic energy.
The European Union recognizes that India is a major emerging democratic power that should be given a broader voice in international affairs, but member countries have yet to agree on their support for New Delhi for its candidacy as a permanent member of the UN Security Council.
They did not delay too much on this issue, yesterday, at this 9th summit organized in Marseille.
The French President, Nicolas Sarkozy, as well as the current President of the Union, as well as the President of the Commission José Manuel Barroso and the head of diplomacy, Javier Solana, welcomed the Indian Prime Minister, Manmohan Singh, with whom they agreed that in five years, they would double trade, which means an increase of a good hundred billion euros.
Taking into account that between 2000 and 2007, trade in goods increased from 25 billion to 55 billion, this does not seem to be an overly ambitious objective.
In this regard, they have legally harmonised the 26 bilateral agreements with India on civil flights, so that air trade can also flourish in the future.
India would like to sign a free trade agreement with the EU by the end of 2009.
Sarkozy has promised to speed up the negotiations.
The aim is to balance the situation with India, the EU's largest trading partner, and New Delhi, which ranks ninth among the EU's partners.
The summit focused on global affairs.
The situation in Afghanistan and Pakistan was strongly condemned, as well as all forms of terrorism, and the urgency of holding a United Nations conference on this issue was raised.
The completion of the Doha trade round was also called for, although both played a large part in the current failure.
The EU has confirmed that it remains true to the energy and climate agenda, notably that it would like to reduce its releases of toxic materials by at least 20 per cent until 2020.
India also agreed on this point, as well as the fact that it would have to pass a global market at next year's climate conference, and reduce greenhouse gas emissions by fifty percent by 2050.
They would also like to prevent the rise in food prices, and supported the convening of an international working meeting to discuss the financial crisis.
The Indian head of state is visiting the French capital today, where at a bilateral meeting he is preparing to sign an agreement on the peaceful use of atomic energy.
In Paris, it is hoped that French companies will receive orders worth 20 billion euros for the construction of Indian atomic reactors.
According to information from the news agency, the agreement would cover 15 years.
In Frankfurt, more than three hundred Italian publishers
Strong presence of Italian publishers at the Frankfurt International Book Fair.
More than three hundred Italian publishers attended the 60th edition of Buchmesse, the most important international event in the exchange of rights.
The Frankfurt International Book Fair awaits for this edition, more than 7 miles of exhibitors from 101 different countries who will occupy the 171,790 square meters of the fair with more than 403 thousand titles on display, and Turkey as guest of honor.
It will be the Assistant Secretary of the Ministry of Properties and Cultural Activities, Francesco Maria Giro, who will represent the Italian Government, during the inauguration ceremony of the Italian Butterfly: in fact, Italy will be present institutionally, with a Point Italy- 264 square meters of exhibition space.
It will be followed by a meeting with the press in the Room Struktur, at the 5.0 butterfly of the Buchmesse: an opportunity to present the figures, trends and prospects on the position of the edition in Italy.
According to the data, the importance of foreign author books is gradually decreasing in relation to the total Italian production, and in particular, in relation to that for adults and children.
Steve Fossett's plane was found missing a year ago.
The wreckage of the plane of Steve Fosset, the billionaire who disappeared on September 3, 2007 while flying over the Nevada desert, has been found.
The debris was found on a plateau at an altitude of 3,000 meters, in the Sierra Nevada area of Mammonth Lakes, on the border between California and Nevada.
Inside the plane, however, no human remains.
Madera County Sheriff John Anderson said: “The plane has been located, we have sent a team, and now we have confirmation that it is indeed the one Steve Fosset was traveling on the day he disappeared.”
The sheriff said no human remains were found on or near the plane.
In February, the 63-year-old billionaire was considered dead.
The U.S. Bureau of Transportation Security (NTSB) said that a few hours after the wreckage was located, a team of investigators sent to the scene identified the aircraft: it was the Bellanca 8kcab, which disappeared on September 3, 2007, when Fosset took off from Yerington, Nevada for a three-hour flight.
Yesterday, also in California, not far from the Nevada border, some of Fosset’s personal belongings were found by a couple around their home in Mammoth Lakes.
These are two documents bearing the name of Fosset, both issued by the Federal Aviation Administration of Illinois, cash and a sweater.
Fossett's search was interrupted a month after his disappearance.
The billionaire had earned a place in history thanks to a long series of records.
At the sixth attempt, in 2002, he became the first man to complete the round the world on an aerostatic balloon: two weeks of solo flight.
Three years later, he had travelled around the world by plane and non-stop.
Among all these records, also that of having flown at 15,445 meters high, on the Andes, but with a co-pilot.
Glk, the ad you don't expect.
An unusual 4x4 of an original and well-defined design, with marked lines, large surfaces and sharp angles.
Here, in summary, Glk, the latest born of the off-road "compact" of the star house, with which Mercedes-Benz has tried to give a wind of novelty in this sector.
Precisely because of its out-of-standard, unexpected and unconventional content will be the communication that will accompany the launch of the 4x4 Glk, available in the Mercedes-Benz showrooms, from October 17.
Thus the hype that will accompany the start of the new car will give rise to an unprecedented mode of communication, through a futuristic campaign of 3D displays, used for the first time in Italy by an automotive brand.
A project of maxi displays, articulated in three different phases, which will dominate the heart of Milanese shopping, Corso Como, until November 15.
The first phase of this new type of communication foresees the presentation of the car in stereoscopic vision, and thanks to special glasses distributed around Corso Como, it will be possible to see the new 4x4 in almost real dimensions and in three-dimensional format.
Indeed, we will have the impression that when looking at the image, the car leaves the poster.
Then, through the use of the innovative Elimina8 technology, the new Glk will be illuminated according to the spots, in all its details, and then recomposed into a single image.
It is obvious that with this advertisement, Mercedes tries to introduce something new in the stereotypical field of motorist communication.
Will it succeed with this formula to arouse the interest of future acquirers? We will see.
